data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in **span conversions** make `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` a better overload match than `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when the receiver is an array. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so this fails at runtime.

## Fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting or calling explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`).
